    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT256-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">poruḷ vilakkappaṭṭa kiḻavaṉ celavaḻuṅkiyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What dispenses with going by HIM who was attracted by
          wealth. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT256">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>maṇivārn taṉṉa mākkoṭi yaṟukai</l>
          <l>piṇikāṉ meṉkompu piṇaiyoṭu mārnta</l>
          <l>māṉē ṟukaḷuṅ kāṉam piṉpaṭa</l>
          <l>viṉainalam paṭīi varutu mavvarait</l>
          <l>tāṅka lollumō pūṅkuḻai yōyeṉac</l>
          <l>collā muṉṉar nillā vāki</l>
          <l>nīrvilaṅ kaḻita lāṉā</l>
          <l>tērvilaṅ kiṉavāṟ ṟerivai kaṇṇē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent">“We shall come when work has turned out well,</l>
          <l rend="indent">afterwards <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">piṉ-paṭa</term> can be
            understood as a variant spelling of <term xml:lang="ta">piṟpaṭu</term> , which is
            rendered in the TL as “to be behind, in time or place”. The infinitive, then, can be
            taken as an adverbial form.</note> , through the forest where the stag <note place="foot">Why <term xml:lang="ta">māṉ-ēṟu</term> , a double-designation of the male
            animal?</note> bounces about</l>
          <l rend="indent2">who has become full along with the doe from the tender twigs</l>
          <l rend="indent8">with linking stalks <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">piṇi kāl meṉ
            kompu</term> ? This description of the Aṟukai is difficult. Is it a creeper (<term xml:lang="ta">koṭi</term>), a grass (TL; <term xml:lang="ta">kāl</term> ) or a shrub
            with twigs (<term xml:lang="ta">kompu</term> )? T.V.G. explains that it has soft twigs,
            but that its stems are firmly rooted in the ground so that it is hard to pluck.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent5">of the Aṟukai, the big creepers as if dripping with jewels. <note place="foot">That is, the rain drops, thus specifying the time of his proposed return
            as the rainy season (cf. KT 104.2). T.V.G., however, wants to take it as part of the
            description of the <term xml:lang="ta">Aṟukai</term> grass itself, which is supposed to
            be dark green/blue: "as if sapphires had been spread".</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent">Is it possible to endure that much, o you with the flower earring?”</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[Even] before [that] was said – without standing [still],</l>
          <l>unending in desolation, for water to be transverse, <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vilaṅku</term> : T.V.G. thinks that the eyes of the formerly happy
            woman are "crying, for a change", but I think it is better to take this literally and
            fitting the image of hyperbole: the water cried by the woman is so much that it can be
            called "transverse", like elsewhere the mountains (cf. KT 134.7, 144.7, 262.6).</note>
          </l>
          <l>they did hinder the chariot, the eyes of the woman.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
